The biggest risk in this moment is something sociologists call â€œsymbolic compliance.â€ Thatâ€™s when an institution that is violating civil rights gives the public just enough symbolic victories that accountability efforts lose steam before there has been any meaningful change.

The problem with symbolic compliance isnâ€™t just that they fall short of ending violence. Itâ€™s also that people duped by the symbols will switch sides to defend the oppressor, emboldening them to become more violent and violate more civil rights than before.

So keep pushing. Anything short of ICEâ€™s abolition isnâ€™t nearly enough. And Iâ€™d say that even ICEâ€™s abolition should only be the start of ending the violence that came to feel â€œnormalâ€ under Trump.

A lot of replies and quotes about Black Lives Matter and #MeToo. And YES. Anything you saw people in power do in response to those movements? Those are the red flags of symbolic compliance. We need big structural changes that would fundamentally make our society less violent and more equal.

See also: anyone who says more training and banning masks for ICE would be enough for them to vote for increased DHS funding. It isnâ€™t enough. Those types of reforms make the violence easier to witness (from a far away position of privilege), but they donâ€™t actually make it stop.

Calls for people to film events in Minnesota reflect good intentions, but intention without process produces unusable evidence. Evidence collected for awareness & evidence collected for legal accountability are not the same activity. They require different standards, safeguards, and infrastructure.

Mass filming raises unresolved structural questions: storage, access, verification, metadata preservation, archiving, and chain of custody. Without trained volunteers, defined workflows, and appropriate tools, large volumes of footage collapse into disorder rather than accountability.

In legal settings, how evidence is gathered and processed often matters more than what it shows. Poor process can render strong evidence useless. If people like Tim Walz ask citizens to document events, they inherit responsibility for defining where that material goes and how it is governed.
Opaque submission portals and poorly designed platforms are not support, they are dead ends. These efforts need systems, training, and clear intent, not just calls to record.

Bellingcat has built and used such systems across conflicts and protests. The challenge is not knowledge, the challenge is deployment and reach. Without structured support, todayâ€™s evidence risks becoming tomorrowâ€™s lost archive, with no accountability outcome at all.
